Food is to blame for European inflation
The main reason for the rise in inflation measured in the eurozone is the rapidly rising food prices.
In the 13 eurozone countries, inflation was higher than expected in November – after 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was registered, according to the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts are only 3%, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the U.S., British, and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered Leitzins, and it considers that the cut in interest rates would favor the rise in commodity prices and the slight decline in unemployment to create a spiral of inflation.
The ECB is striving to keep the inflation rate below 2%, or at least close to the 2% mark.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in a struggling situation: inflation has to be "arranged" in order to rule out the need for action later on.
At 3.3 percent, the inflation rate in Germany reached a twelve-year record high in November; in Spain, the rate climbed from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
The rise in inflation in the eurozone is due to the rise in food and energy prices.
MATIF wheat listings rose by 88 percent, and the price for soybeans also reached a record high since 1973.
There was also a significant inflation in 2007 for edible oil and dairy products.
The world market price of crude oil rose by 52 percent this year – last month, the price per barrel of black gold reached nearly $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent in 2008, but it is expected to fall to 1.9 percent in 2009.
Analysts expect a 3% inflation rate for the next 3-4 months, but estimate the annual average rate at 2.1 percent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice.
Gallup Reports Government Crisis
After long stagnation, the number of Fidesz sympathizers has grown significantly until the beginning of December. For the first time since 2002, the party has the largest base camp, while the approval for the socialists has reached an unprecedented low of 13 percent, according to Gallup.
For party-loyal voters, the difference is clear thanks to the high determination of the opposition supporters: more than two-thirds (71 percent) face one-fifth (20 percent) of the vote for the MSZP.
According to the survey, MDF and SZDSZ are below the parliamentary entry barrier: They come to two percent in the total population.
The number of party voters in both camps has grown by one percent.
Compared to the last low, the overall economic mood has deteriorated further - never before has the proportion of those who consider the country's economic situation to be "extremely bad" been so high (41 percent), while another 46 percent consider it to be "pretty bad".
After more hopeful prospects in spring and summer, families see the change in their financial situation again more pessimistic.
For the coming year, the majority of the population expects a further deterioration of the situation; only a tenth expects an improvement.
A Gallup survey conducted in December found that 71% of respondents – a historic high – rated the Prime Minister’s work as “rather bad than right.”
Thirteen percent of respondents have great confidence or confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány in general, while the proportion of supporters of Viktor Orbán accounts for 38 percent.
Around 54% do not trust the leader at all, compared to 27% distrust of the Fidesz party leader.
One of the indicators of political sentiment is the number of people who believe that dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister could be managed even without a change of government.
After the riots last October, if 35% of the votes were in favour of the remainder of the government and the head of government, this share today amounts to only 20%, while the relative majority (33 percent) sees the solution only in new elections.
Asked about their interest in the referendum, 60 percent replied that they would participate "with certainty", and another 20 percent would "probably" cast their vote.
By way of comparison, if the parliamentary elections were to take place on this Sunday, only 55 percent would go to the polls "with certainty", while another 15 percent would consider their participation to be "probable".
74% would vote against the tuition fees, 79% against the practice fee, and 84% against the hospital day allowance.
If transferred to the group of "certainly" participants in the referendum, the share of opponents of the study, practice and hospital fees would even be 81, 84 and 89 percent, respectively.
