Many places save on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections were registered in hospitals due to improper use of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in hospitals, the overcrowding of beds, the overburden of personnel - all factors that are not exactly beneficial to the containment of infections, according to the senior physician of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
MRSA infection has recently been diagnosed in the traumatology department of János Hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, there was a similar infection.
The victim of a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital, but a short time later the man had to return with an MRSA infection. An important operation has not been performed since because of the bacterium that is still in the patient’s body.
By 10 December of this year, 1094 infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were reported to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System from hospitals, according to the senior physician of the National Epidemiology Center, Karolina Böröcz.
So many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been registered in hospitals with certainty, but the dark figure is likely to be higher.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) were caused by MRSA, the methicillin-oxacillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of people in their nose without causing any disease.
SA-related infections (such as throat inflammation, tonsillitis, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the agents are dosed too high or inappropriately used, the well-responsive bacteria produce antibiotic-resistant, which spread quickly in the hospitals under corresponding conditions.
Especially in patients with weakened, or permanently poorly functioning immune systems, but also in older, or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause serious infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of the János hospital, the MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of the hospital’s daily routine.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, Tibor Nyulasi warned - MRSA does not exist only where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the nurses wear rubber gloves and masks during care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for treatment," says Tibor Nyulasi.
While patients are examined for MRSA when they are admitted to the hospital, infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling too rarely
The majority of MRSA-induced infections in hospitals would be avoidable, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavorable to curbing the development or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
After this infection occurs predominantly in hospitals and retirement homes, hospitals should examine the admitted patients and isolate MRSA-infected immediately.
In Hungarian hospitals, however, microbiological sampling is not practiced as often.
Not least because there are no subsidies from the state health insurance company for this investigation.
Most cases would therefore only come to light when the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology center.
There are strict recommendations from the European Union on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, that is, microbiological examinations are necessary so that no resistance to the drug can form, but this directive is also not always adhered to by hospitals.
Among the outpatient patients or those in primary care, microbiological sampling is even rarer, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Save on Disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most commonly transmitted from one patient to another by nurses.
This is precisely why hand washing or wearing gloves and masks is of great importance, but there are also considerable shortcomings in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted through droplet infection or contact, but in home hospitals there is not always the possibility of isolating the infected patient.
The rooms are even often crowded, the beds lined closely together, although there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them from an epidemiological point of view.
As Karolina Böröcz further notes, unfortunately in the less financially well-off hospitals it even happens that disinfectants are saved, there are few nurses, many patients - all factors that actually favor the development of infections.
Such infections are shown to be far less common there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped, where these protective measures are observed, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Government program against MRSA
Getting MRSA infections under control causes enormous costs to health insurance companies, so they are being combated everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its containment, was recorded in the government program.
At first glance, the program is successful - as published data show, the tendency of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has made the prevention of the development of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals one of its priorities.
