Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is fabulous - all of Europe is attentive to the previously rarely mentioned Balkan state.
What, where, and who still buys the cheapest market in the EU, but it is rapidly getting more expensive?
An analysis of the Bulgarian Re/Max Division.
Bulgaria is currently undoubtedly the most sought after pavement for real estate purchases in Eastern Europe, with cheap ski apartments and houses by the sea.
Between the mountains, the regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are among the most popular, by the sea are Albena, the "Gold Coast", the "Sun Coast", and the historic towns of Sozopol and Nessebar the racers, but real estate around Kavarna and Balcik are also in increasing demand.
According to estimates by Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, the interior of the country will sooner or later attract investors, such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, and Triavna, and also the extremely favourable area of Russe has more buyers.
The capital Sofia also offers tempting offers - commercial and office spaces offer the highest returns.
Bulgaria is well on its way to becoming one of the most attractive European golfing paradises, attracting tourists in addition to the summer and winter seasons, as well as in the other two seasons.
Forward-looking investors are therefore already buying on a large scale, for example around Bansko.
According to analysts, people who buy real estate in Bulgaria are also striving for a change in their lifestyle.
Most buyers are English, but there are also prospective buyers from France, Belgium, Spain, and more and more from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, while there are mainly Russian buyers at the Black Sea and in the ski resorts.
There are three groups of foreign buyers, says Georgij Jankov, regional director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle down buy either revitalized properties for 50-100,000 euros, or degraded houses for 5-15,000 euros, which they then renovate themselves.
Good connectivity and accessibility as well as communication possibilities are of great importance, but also the proximity to a large city, shops and doctors are crucial for the buyers.
The second category includes those who are looking for a holiday home (Bulgaria was listed among the top ten holiday destinations of the Germans in December).
The third group is made up of business people who invest with the aim of increasing their value in the medium to long term.
However, real estate in the capital is constantly becoming more expensive, due to the ever-growing demand.
Within the EU, property prices are the lowest in Bulgaria, but in the last five years there has been a 21 percent annual price increase.
The increase in real estate prices far exceeds the increase in salaries.
Fodor and the Six Hungarian Percents
As Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue by the ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which sets out the emission reduction measures for the period after 2012, i.e. after the expiry of the Kyoto Protocol.
A fierce debate is currently taking place between developed and developing countries.
The U.S. has already signalled that it does not want to negotiate concrete figures, but it would be ready to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other big question of the conference is whether the developed countries are willing to provide both financial and technological support to developing countries in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement was also reached on support for developing countries.
The adjustment fund, which is subject to the Kyoto Protocol, is to be managed by a 16-member council, which is expected to be administered by the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), as can be seen in the "Piac és Profit".
Hungary 6%
On behalf of Hungary, Environment Minister Gábor Fodor supports the EU’s efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate action and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister said the EU would reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (measured at 1990 levels), regardless of whether the "post-2012 agreement" was successfully achieved or not. The Union would even be willing to commit to a 30% reduction, provided other major industrialised countries of the world, or developing countries, are also willing to do their utmost and responsibly.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the goal of the states that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 percent, whereas the EU, with its then 15 member states, had already committed to a reduction of 8%.
The target for Hungary is a 6% reduction in greenhouse gas emissions compared to 1985-87 - a target that the country will certainly meet, as can be seen in the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The commitment is high in Bali - after all, the long-term international climate agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly only come into force after 2012. In this case, the reduction plans set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not follow a new international emission reduction system, the importance of which has also been highlighted by the IPCC, the most recent international scientific climate change committee awarded with the Nobel Peace Prize in its UN report.
This would delay the reduction of emissions and increase the Earth’s average temperature by more than 2°C would be unavoidable, which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irreparable consequences.
British Army Advertises on YouTube
Units of the British Army have published footage of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan for the purpose of increasing popularity on the video portal.
First, the British Air Force (RAF) discovered YouTube for itself: Special forces stationed in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of operations against the Taliban on the net since March 2006, reports the BBC.
The shots filmed with miniature cameras attached to helmets are controlled at the Air Force Base in Kandahar and then sent to London, where they are posted on the Internet.
Political message unavoidable
Soldiers of the Luftwaffe have already contributed 139 such recordings, their "channel" has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The British Ministry of Defense was registered under "defenceheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 to publish videos about Iraqi and Afghan operations, but also the British Foreign Office and Iraqi-based international peacekeeping forces (MNFI) have their own YouTube channels.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally, the Air Force published the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and as the Ministry of Defence says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the population about the actual objectives of foreign operations.
According to defense expert Gordon Mackenzie of the BBC, this kind of propaganda is almost free of charge, but these videos always carry a certain amount of political message, as they confirm the rightful existence of the military measures decided by the government in their own way.
Americans advertise with game
But the army must also fight against amateur shots, which, in addition to the carefully edited, censored shots, also make it onto the net - such as those that show the death of the soldiers: In the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films, the losses are talked about at most, but the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
By the way, numerous videos shot in action have already been uploaded from the war venues in Iraq and Afghanistan, but this "genre" has only recently been discovered by the British.
However, the Americans advertise in a slightly different way, namely with the freely downloadable shooting game "Americas Army", in which the player can slip into the skin of the soldier as part of a more or less lifelike simulation.
