Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Increases State Risk
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded this August with the support of the "Movement for a Better Hungary", have increased the risk of Hungary and the region in several ways.
In connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the highest political risk is the exacerbation of the existing ethnic tensions between the Gypsies and non-Gypsies population in Hungary, which could even lead to violent ethnic conflicts in the short term.
The main reason for this is the strategy of the Hungarian Guard, which is probably aimed at provoking such a confrontation, according to the research institute.
As reported, this is seen as a failure on the part of the political leaders: "Public authorities have left the discussion of the Roma question to representatives of radical political groups who have now built their political strategy on the Roma-Hungary contrast."
It is believed that this would exacerbate the problem, make reasonable dialogue impossible, promote extremities, and increase the likelihood of violent clashes.
The research institute also believes that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, not least thanks to the enormous attention of the domestic and foreign media, "have significantly damaged the image of Hungary abroad, in particular in terms of confidence in stability and democratic maturity".
We remember that since the autumn of 2006, the reorganization of radical and extreme right-wing groups in Hungary is continually on the rise, so that since the summer of 2007, several organizations called "national self-defense associations" have been founded.
"These groups have in common the fact that they each define themselves as a civilian organization, while they openly boast of preparing their members for - sometimes armed - defense tasks (disaster protection, national defense, security), citing the inadequacy of the police, the army, or the state itself," it said.
And further: all this is done according to that method, which seeks to disguise various political aspirations as bourgeois initiative, based on the political and party-worship of the population.
The emphasis on the civil character and the form of association therefore serves not only to circumvent legal hurdles that could arise in the course of registration in court - it is at the same time a political strategy.
As the analysis shows, the activities of the Hungarian Guard also represent a risk-increasing factor for relations with neighbouring countries.
In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been cited as a potential source of danger in several neighboring states, as some ultra-nationalist politicians in certain neighboring countries see the emergence of the Hungarian Guard as a confirmation of its own anti-Hungarian policy.
All of this has an impact on the political stability of the region,” he said.
From the point of view of the research institute, the establishment of the Hungarian Guard is not a single phenomenon in Central Eastern Europe, so the political risk for the entire region has grown.
As reported, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are comparable to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, whose establishment was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
In the background of the creation of the Bulgarian Guard were the Roma riots that took place in a neighbourhood of Sofia (Krasna Poljana).
The BNU took the incidents as an occasion for the establishment of the National Guard, arguing that the goal of the organization is "national protection".
