Holidays are not holidays everywhere
In Hungary, holidays are strictly regulated by law, so the practice of rearranging the working days around the holidays has now become established, but the coming year will give us fewer such days.
Also in the EU and in America, something else is understood as "holiday".
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between public holidays and days off.
Unemployment days are usually church holidays, or are related to significant historical events.
For example, we also celebrate New Year: both the last day of the old year and the first day of the new year are days without work - the latter alone so that the New Year's Eve celebraters can rest.
Throughout the year we have a total of fourteen holidays.
The state holidays are March 15, commemorating the Revolution of 1848, and October 23, commemorating the Revolution of 1956.
On the 20th of August we celebrate the founding of the state, on the 1st of May we celebrate the work, on the 1st and 2nd of November we commemorate our dead.
In addition, there are two holidays each for Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national, or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of "working day shift" has proven itself in cases where we would work just one day before or after the holiday.
The price of the extended weekends, however, is that we have to work very well on the Saturdays before it, or go to school.
When this day, which falls before or after the holiday, is to be finalized, has been determined for many years by the Minister of Labour in his own regulation.
The legislation applies to all employers and contractors, to public employees and civil servants alike.
Excluded are only companies and facilities in which the operation is continued without interruption, i.e. even on holidays.
This year, the working order is only slightly confused by the holidays at the end of the year: From 24 December, life in this country will be formally halted, since most take time compensation for the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve, or the specially cancelled holiday.
Next year, more holidays will fall in the middle of the week, or at the end of the week, so there will be fewer re-dispositions during the working days than this year.
The calendar is first "turned upside down" around the day of work so that people can stay at home for four days at a time.
Saturday the 26th of April will be a working day so that Friday the 2nd of May can be a day of rest.
The second rearrangement is related to the holiday on October 23rd: on Saturday, October 18th, you will have to work the Friday, October 24th in advance.
The end of the year, however, will be completely under the banner of holidays, after all lies and stands still from December 24th, even if New Year's Eve falls on a Wednesday.
Six dissuasive trifles to annoy workmates
E-mails that we forget to send, voice messages that we never receive - harmless lies that we no longer notice: They bring "colour" into everyday workplace life.
The only question is whether you get used to these small inconveniences, or you better take up the challenge and try to avoid these misunderstood, consciously for other annoying situations.
Tips.
"Sorry, I forgot to tell you that someone from the marketing department called" - says one colleague.
Did you miss a meeting?
At best, you regret it and try to make up for it by perhaps calling the marketing department and confessing with remorse that you forgot to direct the message (this is the less common method).
Usually, this is done with an apology.
Before you get caught up in embarrassing excuses, you should consider what you can do to prepare your colleagues for truly unpleasant moments and consciously try to avoid these situations.
Borrow something that doesn’t belong to you?
There’s hardly anything more annoying than reaching for a document, office supplies, or the phone, but it’s not there.
Yesterday the stapler was still on the desk - this morning it's gone?
Or is the lost ballpoint pen discovered on a colleague’s desk?
Without question, you should not borrow anything from your colleagues, because they are rightly upset when they find that something has gone away.
So, don't put envelopes or post-it out of the office in your pocket, because it could hit you yourself: no more there, if you need it urgently.
Talk about the private lives of your colleagues?
There is no effective means of stopping a gossip that has already been put into the world.
Who to whom, what to do?
Where and why?
You should not tie the information (or assumptions) about the private lives of colleagues to everyone's nose if possible!
And if someone opens up and tells us his innermost secret, we should not abuse that trust!
It is best to remain silent like a grave, rather than aligning the one who is not present, even if others know about the problems of the colleague.
Reported ill for no reason?
When you call in the office to report sick, citing an agonizing headache, because you are feeling uncomfortable at the moment, or just want to rest, you should be aware of one thing: Your own work, irrevocable completions, projects with fixed deadlines now have to be done by colleagues instead of yourself.
So don’t play along with your colleagues!
If you already know the day before that you will not be able to get to the office the next day, or that something could interfere, which is why you have to stay at home, you should report it in time, so that neither the colleagues nor the boss are unexpectedly confronted with the absence.
Calling, calling, calling
One is currently immersed in his work, but is suddenly disturbed by the loud jokes of the colleagues?
Did you hear a phone call that you shouldn’t have heard?
You should not annoy colleagues with humming, singing, loud conversations (which you run over their heads), trampled, constant scolding or nagging.
All of this can be very disturbing, even if you are not deeply involved in a task (writing, planning, organizing).
Is it always the other people's fault?
If a project is not finished on time, you have forgotten to send an important letter or important messages, you should not look for the fault of your own forgetfulness in others!
If possible, you should not talk about the chaos in the office or the noisy colleagues!
It is best to confess your mistakes and apologize if others were affected.
The question of how to make up for the mistake, or make up for the missed, is all too appropriate!
In the office - a feeling like home?
Training pants and trousers: Comfortable for home, but has nothing to lose in the office!
Not even then should one dress so casually, if the workplace would actually allow it!
Just don't get too sloppy - you should respect both your colleagues and yourself to the extent that you dress accordingly in the office - if desired, also pretty and elegant!
