Banks want to tackle the crisis
The US Federal Reserve, the European Central Bank and the central banks of Great Britain, Switzerland and Canada have decided to fight together against the crisis in the financial markets.
More than $100 billion will go to the currency markets through auctions.
At these auctions, the banks auction interest rates to which they are willing to lend money to each other.
For example, the US Fed sends $40 billion to auction, another 24 makes it loose for the European and Swiss central banks.
It is the first time, after the September 11 attacks, that the central banks of the individual states have agreed on such a coordinated approach to defend themselves or mitigate the consequences of a financial crisis.
“This move aims to eliminate the biggest difficulties the economy faces, i.e. the increasing shortage of freely available capital that banks can lend,” said Bernard Baumohl, a consultant for Economic Outlook Group.
“The coordinated action by central banks has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the U.S. from 65% to about 50%,” Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion due to unserved loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts are expecting billions more.
“The central banks must have been really afraid of what could happen after deciding to do this,” said ABN Amro chief economist Kieran Davies.
"It looks like the situation is really bad," he said.
Central banks fear that if the banks themselves have difficulty accessing bonds, loans will also become more expensive for their customers.
That would reduce consumption and plunge the American economy into a recession, potentially impacting economic growth around the world.
The central banks have decided to do so after failing to lower the so-called LIBOR, the London interbank interest rate used in lending money between banks.
This means that banks were constantly afraid to lend money to each other, even though the central banks of the U.S., Canada, and the UK had lowered interest rates several times during the fall.
“This will have the same effect as further lowering interest rates,” Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
Some analysts believe that this move by central banks is contributing to warming up the crisis because it does not solve the basic problem, namely the fall of the US real estate market.
