Cuba - the most beautiful island in the Caribbean
For visitors, it is truly an island of freedom.
Whatever you expect from your holidays, it will come true if you only choose the right one.
Golden and white beaches, high waves or a sea that is quiet like a pond.
Palms and All Inclusive with waiters offering pizza, ice cream and seductive cocktails on the beach.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean you will find this in abundance.
But only on one island you will find much more, and this island is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful of the Greater Antilles.
At the time of the Spanish, Cuba was their bastion for the conquest of America.
Columbus called it the most beautiful place a human eye has ever seen.
Havana once became a camp or transit camp of treasures that the Spaniards had stolen in America and then transported to Europe.
Then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was built at the end of the 20th century.
It was built by one of the chiefs of the American mafia, Lucky Luciano, because everything that was considered a crime in the United States (especially during the prohibition) was welcomed and supported in Cuba - drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his guests were, among others,
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, high-rise buildings grew, over the wide boulevards drove cars, which were among the cult symbols of the fifties of the last century.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Cojímar he had his yacht lying.
On the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio, stars of show business and politicians from all over America left their signatures.
What about today?
You can also leave your autograph on the walls of the Bodeguita of Havana.
At the bar at the Hotel Nacional you can mix cocktails to your liking.
And the cult cars of the 1950s continue to drive around in Havana today, because the once imported Schigulis and Fiats in the salty and damp air have long since fallen apart.
Havana, especially its oldest part, may have been severely degraded, nowhere else can you find as many wonderful colonial sights as right here.
Other places are just being cleaned out, for example, Trinidad.
In view of the fact that tourism brings much-needed money, there was a green light for this development.
In the last fifteen years, new hotels have emerged not only in Havana, but also in Varadero, on the coast of the province of Holguín and also on islets such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba still offers a moth that is unique in the world and especially attracts railway enthusiasts.
The sugar cane from remote plantations brought steam and diesel-driven narrow-gauge railways to the sugar factories.
Their fleet has not been renewed for decades, and so you can see cute and fully functioning locomotives, whose peers have long since been in the museum elsewhere.
Excursions
The most important places do not leave out the majority of visitors to Cuba.
So you no longer have to write about Varadero or Havana in detail.
Let's just mention that the Hemingway estate has a museum, which should not be missed by anyone who likes this writer.
The Viñales Valley in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
The lush vegetation grows on lime soil.
The mogotas, limestone hills and rocks, rise steeply from the valley floor, in their cavities fertile soil accumulated, by which even weathered rock areas are covered by dense vegetation.
This valley is where perhaps the best Cuban tobacco is grown.
In its final form, you can meet him when you visit one of the cigar factories of Havana.
It may also seem interesting to some that the Chilean episode of the television series "Major Zeman" was filmed there.
Trinidad
An ancient city founded shortly after the Spanish colonized the island.
Fame and wealth brought her the trade in slaves and sugar.
The richness embodied in the beautiful beauty of the small town.
Spanish colonial architecture, heavily influenced by the later French settlers, has hardly changed in four hundred years.
Trinidad, located between the sea and the Escambray Mountains, is such a remote place that in the 1950s there was no road that would have connected the area with the rest of the country.
This insulation helped to keep it unnoticed.
Nothing was built there, but therefore nothing was torn down, everyone was glad he had a roof over his head.
If you have more than an afternoon for Trinidad, then it is worth visiting interesting places in the area, such as the Playa Ancón beach or the "Valle of the Sugar Factory".
In the evening you should then go to the Casa de la Música, which revives after dark, and where the music does not remain silent until the morning.
Baracoa
This small town in the east of Cuba is considered by some to be the most beautiful on the island.
Certainly this view is also influenced by the way there.
Both roads leading from Guantánamo must overcome high and rugged mountains and run through a landscape barely touched by human intervention.
This eastern outpost of Cuba was included by UNESCO in its World Heritage List thanks to its unspoilt nature.
There the best chocolate is made, in the church you can see the cross of Columbus (in reality it was created about a hundred years after the trips of Columbus), and from the hill where the former castle, the current Hotel El Castillo, stands, you can see several table mountains, of which El Yunque is the most famous.
About the coffee, the rum, the cigars, the Sierra Maestra mountains, the bay of pigs and the island of Isla de Pinos, about the Tropicana cabaret, the sanctuary of the Cuban patron Caridad del Cobre, about the santeria, an African religion that the descendants of slaves profess, many pages could be written about.
As they say, it’s better to look with your own eyes.
Allies in Afghanistan are passive, Americans claim.
According to the United States, too few soldiers and the lack of necessary equipment influence the course of the mission in Afghanistan.
NATO should design a concrete plan for the coming years, according to Defense Secretary Robert Gates.
The mission in Afghanistan did not run according to their ideas, and in Edinburgh, Scotland, the representatives of the countries that have deployed units in the south of the country agreed on this.
In addition to the growing resistance on the part of the Taliban, the eight participating states are also discussing further coordination plans among the allies.
While the United States, through its Secretary of Defense Robert Gates, called on NATO units to take more action, Britain sees the priority in strengthening the authority of the Afghan government and intensifying development aid.
“Afghanistan is moving forward, but military power can only be part of the solution.
Another part is enabling residents to start developing the economy and security themselves," Des Browne, the British defense minister, told the BBC.
Ninety percent
The activity of the Afghan insurgents has reached the highest level in five years, according to the American army.
The number of violent actions has increased by 27 percent compared to the previous year, in the southern province of Helmand even by sixty percent.
The NATO countries have stationed about 40,000 soldiers in Afghanistan, about a quarter of them in southern territory.
According to the United States, however, the allies have reached an absolute limit in terms of organization and equipment of the units.
Specifically, they call for more helicopters, soldiers and experts to train Afghan units.
"We'll have to seriously think about the concrete goals for the next time and the way we can achieve them," Gates said.
NATO Secretary-General Jaap de Hoop said the same thing today.
"I am not pleased with what we have available in Afghanistan on land and in the air.
We have about ninety percent of the soldiers and equipment we need, and that's too little," De Hoop told Reuters at the end of three-day talks with the Japanese government in Tokyo.
Who is passive
In recent months, there has also been a dispute among the countries involved as to whether all allies in Afghanistan are doing their best.
Germany, for example, was criticized for its passivity.
"The Germans are relatively numerous in Afghanistan.
But they are stationed in areas where there is only a minimum of violence and the combat requirements for them are not as high as for us in the southern and eastern part of the country," Gates said.
The British tabloid newspaper "Sun" this week described the German soldiers as lazy.
"Afghan non-smokers unmasked: Germans play games while our boys fight," the "Sun" wrote in a post supplemented by photos of German soldiers playing table tennis.
