Debt Grows
The national debt comes from the debt of the state government and comes mainly from the accumulation of deficits in the state budget.
Government debt is financed by treasury notes, government bonds, direct bonds or, for example, by bonds from the European Investment Bank.
Domestic debt has risen to 719.4 billion kroner this year.
The government’s external debt has now risen by 1.7 billion kroner to 123.3 billion.
The so-called marketable government debt reached 803.3 billion kroner at the end of September and has fallen by 13.7 billion since June.
The average maturity of the national debt rose to 6.5 years.
Overall debt rose 13 percent over the year from the first to the third quarter, which is really a lot given how well the economy is doing.
Interestingly, the growth is mainly in debt securities, where the growth is 20 percent.
It's bad that debt is rising, but on the other hand, it shows that you can do something before pension reform comes," Pikora commented on the data.
Better than expected
The financing strategy and government debt management for 2007 shows that the government had planned to raise 159.2 billion kroner for this year.
At the beginning of December, however, thanks to the better development of state budgetary policy, the ministry reduced the plan to 152.8 billion kroner.
This amount is mainly due to the government budget deficit, which will obviously reach 76 billion kroner this year instead of the estimated 91.3 billion.
It also includes a maximum amount of 13.3 billion kroner for the consolidation agency, a ten-billion reserve to pay pensions, 43-billion sovereign bond financing and 1.8-billion instalments for the European Investment Bank’s bonds.
For giving a name to a teddy bear, she was presented to a court in Khartoum today.
According to her lawyer, the British teacher, who had been accused of insulting Islam in Sudan, was sentenced to 15 days in prison and subsequent expulsion by a court in Khartoum on Thursday evening.
The British woman has been accused of allowing six- to seven-year-old students to name a teddy bear Mahomet, although any depiction of the Islamic prophet is forbidden.
She deserved to be whipped.
After parents of students had complained to the Sudanese Ministry of Culture several times, the 54-year-old primary school teacher, who worked at Khartoum’s Unity High School, was picked up at her home on Sunday and accused of insulting Islam under Article 125 of the Sudanese Criminal Code.
In fact, this matter begins in September, when the teacher asks her six- to seven-year-old students to pick a name for the class teddy.
The children suggest eight names, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed, reports school principal Robert Boules.
Finally, when the class votes, 20 out of 23 children choose Mohammed as their favorite first name.
Sure, Muhammad is the name of the Islamic prophet, but above all a very common first name in Sudan.
Afterwards, the children created a book for the class, with the photo of the bear on it and the caption My name is Mohammed.
The bear himself did not wear a shield with that name, but the problem is quite simply that the depiction of the Islamic prophet is considered an insult to Islam.
One of the Muslim colleagues of Gillian Gibbons, who teaches at the same school in Sudan, stated that he knows her well, and she would never have done anything that would have made her too close to a religious belief, I only regret that she asked the children to vote for a name, in his opinion this is just an innocent mistake.
An opinion that many of the teacher’s students share, describing her as very attentive to her students and as a person who never speaks about religion in class.
Keep in mind that the first name Mohammed is also the second most common given second name in the UK, for which there are 14 different spellings in English.
