But what are the rules regarding the use of this first name?
Can you give it to a toy, for example?
This is, of course, a matter of interpretation.
On Wednesday, at the last negotiating session in Vienna, no agreement was reached on the future status of the province.
At the end of the failure
The Serbians and Albanians from Kosovo concluded a sixth and final discussion meeting in Baden, Austria, on Wednesday morning, without being able to overcome their controversies about the future status of the separatist province.
It is regrettable that the parties were unable to reach an agreement on the status, European mediator Wolfgang Ischinger explained at a press conference in Vienna.
Emphasizing that peace in the region is at stake, its American counterpart Frank Wilsner called on Belgrade and Pristina to fulfil their commitments to maintain peace and to continue the talks beyond the end of the negotiations.
No acts of violence are expected in the immediate future, but we are at the beginning of a very difficult time, he added, hinting that there are quite clear tensions.
End of mediation on 10 December
The mediators of the Troika, which unites the European Union, the US and Russia, will meet for the last time in Serbia and Kosovo on Monday.
The future of the 90% Albanian-speaking province could become clearer if Ischinger, Wilsner and Russian mediator Alexander Botsane-Khartchenko submit their report to the UN Security Council by December 10.
The talks in Baden, near Vienna, constituted the sixth and last negotiating session since the Troika was commissioned by the UN in August.
Americans and Europeans expect their mediation mission to end on December 10.
The Russians, who had already blocked the approval of Kosovo’s independence at the Security Council, insist on continuing negotiations beyond this end date.
Russia has been and remains the advocate of a negotiated solution, a consensual solution, Botsane-Khartchenko said.
Unilateral Declaration of Independence?
After Kosovo has been under the administration of the UN for eight years, the Western countries consider independence under EU supervision to be the only solution with a future.
Pristina is ready to unilaterally announce it if the Security Council does not decide in its favor.
Belgrade insists on greater autonomy
Unfortunately, no agreement could be reached, the president of the autonomous authority of Kosovo, Fatmir Sejdiu, announced at the hotel in Baden, where these negotiations were held since Monday the last chance.
Hashim Thaci, former leader of the Kosovar rebellion and future prime minister of the province, shared his regrets.
However, he added that Belgrade’s proposed plan for autonomy belongs to a past that has led to murders and deportations.
Domino effect
Serbian President Boris Tradic, for his part, was of the opinion that a compromise should always be sought, warning the Albanian majority from Kosovo of the consequences of a unilateral declaration of independence of the province.
Belgrade believes that there is a particular "domino effect" in a region that is still weakened by the wars of independence of the 1990s.
For Serbia, this does not mean that a compromise would be impossible, he said.
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation insisted that any decision should be made solely in the Security Council, where its Russian ally has a veto right.
The Parliament of Kosovo will have the last word
Only a decision from the Security Council is acceptable for Serbia, Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica said.
These negotiations took two years.
They must end up as they started: in the Security Council.
Fatmir Sejdiu told the journalists that the parliament of Kosovo would have the last word on the status, adding that any unilateral declaration of independence by the Albanian-speaking population would take place in consultation with the Western countries.
Bush Seeks Agreement Between Israelis and Palestinians
At the opening of the international peace conference, which was held in Annapolis, Maryland, on Tuesday, President Bush announced that Israelis and Palestinians had finally agreed on a joint statement.
He further stated that Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Olmert and Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas had agreed to begin negotiations immediately to find a final settlement of the 60-year-old disputes between their two peoples.
In the presence of the two men, Bush promised that he would do anything to help them sign a peace treaty before the end of 2008.
In the meantime, the Palestinians must destroy the terrorist infrastructures and Israel must stop its colonization work, Bush said, reminding the two parties of their commitments to the roadmap for peace that they agreed to in 2003.
The White House chief stressed that the negotiations between Israel and the Palestinian authorities under Abbas ultimately seek a peace treaty that will clarify all open issues without exception, including the central issues.
This designation covers the three serious problems that the disputes between Israelis and Palestinians mainly revolve around: the future borders of Palestine, the status of Jerusalem and the fate of the Arab refugees who were expelled from their homeland in today’s state of Israel as a result of the 1948 conflict.
After the American president, Abbas took the floor and insisted that the forthcoming negotiations be conducted comprehensively and thoroughly and provide a settlement for all points, including Jerusalem, the refugees, the borders, the colonies, water and security.
When Olmert, for his part, spoke, he pledged to ensure that the forthcoming ceasefire negotiations were conducted directly and without interruption and that he would endeavour to ensure that they could be concluded before the end of 2008.
Bush has set the deadline for implementing his vision of two coexisting states, one Palestinian and one Israeli, by the end of 2008.
Saudi Arabia has disclosed that it has received an assurance from Bush in this sense before deciding to attend the conference.
Arabia, whose participation in Annapolis represents a great success for Washington, has initiated a plan adopted by all Arab countries to offer peace to Israel, in exchange for its withdrawal from all Arab territories occupied during the 1967 war, including East Jerusalem.
Annapolis represents a crossroads in the history of the Middle East, especially because it attacks the roots of the conflict and its central points of view, says the Saudi-Arab prince in his interview with the Saudi-funded Arabic-language daily.
