Spectacular repair at the space station
Astronaut Scott Parazynski and his crewmates from the International Space Station (ISS) will have taken more than seven hours in space to perform the spectacular repair of a defective solar collector, which is essential for the continuation of scientific work on the station.
A daring exit that has achieved several records due to its duration, the removal of habitable modules, the speed with which it was organized, and the tools crafted by the astronauts to carry out the repair.
The problem arose on Wednesday when the astronauts had unloaded the Harmony module from the space shuttle Discovery, a large cylindrical part that is soon to accommodate the European and Japanese scientific laboratories.
This module is a kind of landing bridge for the module laboratories.
But you have to be able to supply them with electricity.
So the crew’s second task was to implement a 17.5-ton solar panel power generating module that was already on the ISS in order to bring it to its final position.
After moving it, the crew began restructuring the solar panels of the module, whose span is 76 meters.
And it happened that one of the collectors, which can be folded up like accordions, was damaged by a pinched cable about a meter long.
The restructuring was stopped in order not to damage the collector even more.
The astronauts, who were originally supposed to leave the Discovery space shuttle for a control walk and then repair another solar collector whose rotation system was faulty, were forced to devote themselves to the damaged collector.
And Scott Parazynski was chosen to walk around at the end of the 30-metre-long remote-controlled arm of the space shuttle that had been attached to the station to carry out the repair.
He is one of NASA's best spacewalkers.
Large, resistant, very skillful, he has a well-developed upper body and long arms.
The 46-year-old trained doctor was thus selected to operate the injured solar panel.
After carefully examining the damage, he cut the faulty cable and fastened a kind of rail to the damaged area.
He was supported by a second spacewalker who remained near the lock, and, from inside, by the other astronauts, among them Peggy Whitson, commander of the crew.
The tool he used, a mini hockey bat, wrapped with insulator to prevent an electric shock on the solar panels, which generate several hundred volts, had been conceived and crafted by the astronauts on board the station.
When the action ended, Scott Parazynski waited until the collector was fully unfolded before counting down his tools and returning to the station.
Yesterday afternoon, the astronauts enjoyed half a day of relaxation before today, seven astronauts returned to the space shuttle Discovery, expected to take the return flight to Earth on Wednesday.
