A heavy memorabilia
After being treated confidentially for more than 60 years, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which are housed in Bad Arolsen on a total length of 27 km, have not been viewed until now, unless with a humanitarian intention, i.e. individually and by name, i.e. at the request of a former victim or his relatives.
In May 2006, the eleven states responsible for its administration – including Germany, France, Israel and the United States – agreed to make it accessible to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process of this decision has been completed, the opening has been valid since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will make it possible to conduct research, especially on the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of the concentration camps and the health status of the forced laborers, explains Reto Meistern, head of these archives, which are administered by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, were opposed to making these names-related documents available to the public, due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
Such as the alleged homosexuality or intellectual disability of some deportation victims.
The inmate lists of the concentration camps or the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo had been compiled after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labour, and possibly to provide them with evidence of their arrest in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen process tens of thousands of personal inquiries.
Nevertheless, a part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in access to Bad Arolsen.
Nothing fundamentally new should be expected in these documents, Pr. Wolfgang Benz, head of the Research Center for Anti-Semitism at the Technical University of Berlin, explained in 2006.
