New fears about natural gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute swells between Ukraine and Russia, which increases the risk that Russian exports of fuel to Western Europe will be affected.
Most of Russia’s natural gas exports to the European Union (EU) are led by Ukraine and any dispute between the two nations is closely monitored.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will charge higher transit fees from Russia.
An earlier conflict between the two states last year reduced deliveries to the EU states.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow happens at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine needs to be charged more, as the group has agreed to pay up to 50% extra for natural gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say that this could mean that Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for the imports of Gazprom.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states in talks," Ukraine's economic minister Anatoli Kinakh told Reuters.
"The changing natural gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the level of transit fees [to Western Europe] via Ukraine."
In the last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom cut supplies to Ukraine.
This led to a fall in exports to Western Europe, which pushed prices up dramatically.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union’s supply.
Russia has the world’s largest gas reserves, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
As a result, Gazprom supplements its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
NHS "must control foreign workers"
The Scottish State Health Service must improve the controls of criminal records for workers from outside Europe, said a member of the control body.
The recommendation of Chief Financial Controller Robert Black came after a foreign doctor in Scotland was brought in connection with the June attack on the Glasgow airport.
Black also expressed concerns that the Scottish State Health Service does not have an accurate idea of the number of its foreign employees.
But his report noted that other important checks were performed correctly on a sample of five health authorities.
The Chief Financial Controller investigated personnel recruited outside the European Economic Area as a result of the Glasgow airport attack.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after an off-road vehicle was driven through the doors of the main airport terminal.
He was one of three doctors who appeared in a video broadcast at the Old Bailey in October and was charged in connection with the alleged car bombing in the UK.
The State Health Service is expected to carry out checks prior to hiring foreign employees to ensure that they have the qualifications, experience and authorizations required to work in the UK.
Although the health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to verify criminal records, the agency does not have the jurisdiction to obtain this information outside of the UK.
The main auditor’s report now states, among other recommendations, that the board should take up criminal record extract guidelines that help employers with checks in different countries.
"Although we found clues to these checks in some personnel records, these were not routinely carried out," the report noted.
Black said the Scottish health authorities would heavily follow their pre-embassy examination guidelines, but added: “Our report highlights areas where the system can be improved to ensure accurate information on the number of foreign health care workers is available.”
BMA Scotland chairman Dr. Peter Terry said it was "extremely unlikely" that investigations in advance of hiring potential NHS employees would identify people who could commit future terrorist attacks.
"The report states that current pre-embassy tests at the NHS Scotland are working well and it is not clear what added value the recommendations will deliver," he said.
The Scottish health authorities say they currently have 1,161 foreign employees, the vast majority of whom are doctors and nurses.
However, the financial controller warned that the number was likely to be higher, partly because the boards had trouble identifying those employees who were on leave for an indefinite period.
The investigation further found that established control procedures were followed by NHS authorities in Ayrshire, Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian.
These include passport, work permit, and qualification checks.
The Scottish government is currently reviewing its policies and guidelines for pre-embassy checks for foreign personnel in the NHS.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: "I was concerned to carry out this work in light of the terrorist attack at Glasgow Airport."
She added that the Scottish government, in conjunction with the health authorities, would take into account the recommendations of the report and ensure that best practices are reflected in updated guidelines regarding pre-employee check-ups by all employees, including those from abroad, whose publication is scheduled for next month.
