The deterioration in rates can be partly explained by technical factors.
A change in U.S. private insolvency laws in 2005 resulted in an abrupt case of bankruptcy filings, which in turn account for much of the debit card losses; the number of filings (and hence default fees) would rise again whether the general conditions for borrowers deteriorate or not.
The industry also reports solid payment rates showing how much of their debt consumers pay off each month
and the trust in credit card-based securities is quite strong, despite the stagnation in other corners of structured financing.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research company, expects that outputs for 2007 will ultimately be 25% higher than last year.
