However, the card issuers look at the money flow rather than capital values, so falling house prices do not necessarily trigger a change in the borrower’s creditworthiness.
They can even be beneficial for the card issuers.
The incentives for consumers to continue paying mortgage rates drop when the real estate value is less than the value of the loan; as a result, card debt becomes more important among the repayment priorities.
Card issuers can also react to the more stormy conditions much faster and more flexibly than lenders by changing interest rates or credit limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risk of a rapid revaluation of the assets.
“We’re not going to wake up one day and reassess the loans entirely,” says Gary Perlin, Capital One’s chief finance officer.
