Venus is the Earth's hellish twin
Despite its hostile atmosphere, Venus is more similar to Earth than previously thought: The European spacecraft "Venus Express" has discovered lightnings in the atmosphere and windswirls at the poles, as they occur on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have suspected that it flashes on Venus.
Now the European probe "Venus Express" has provided the proof - it tracked electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: The lightnings on Venus shoot at an altitude of about 56 kilometers from cloud to cloud, reports Christopher Russel from the University of California in Los Angeles in the science magazine "Nature".
According to the famous "primary soup theory", lightning has created life on Earth: thunderstorms are said to have stimulated reactions in the ocean that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: "If there was ever life there, it must have been in very early history," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there should be hardly anything living on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees.
"Venus may be Earth's devil's twin, but she's a twin," Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and size, has undergone such a completely different development, is the basic question of the Esa mission.
The launch of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was a milestone for Venus research, as since the beginning of the 1990s no probe has been on its way to exploring this planet.
The latest research, now presented in several "Nature" articles, not only underscores the uniqueness of Venus within the Solar System, the researchers said.
“They also show that the similarities between our neighboring planet and Earth are greater than initially thought,” the ESA said.
In addition to the already known whirlwind at the North Pole, the researchers also found a cloud swirl at the South Pole, which rotates even faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents on the earth’s winter hemisphere, writes a research team led by Giuseppe Piccioni from the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second innermost planet in the Solar System has almost the same mass as Earth and is almost the same size with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers.
The planet, also known as the morning or evening star, orbits the sun in just under 225 days.
But it turns much slower around itself: a Venus day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, is hardly reminiscent of Earth, scientists assume that both planets were formed under very similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated, which remained in the oceans on Earth, but was lost in space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide is fixed in carbonate rocks on Earth, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
