These are not Warhol's boxes
Anyone who combines the terms Sweden and wooden box thinks of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Isn't that right?
Currently, wooden boxes manufactured in Sweden cast dark shadows on Warhol’s factory directory.
Most of the ninety-four Stockholm-type Brillo boxes listed there are counterfeit.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" a few months ago raised doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes of 1968, internal investigations at the Moderna Museet in Stockholm now come to a disappointing result: the six "Brillo boxes", which the former museum director Pontus Hultén probably gave to the international art market, the Moderna Museet in 1995 is also a donation.
The prehistory is nested, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo Boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard boxes of the soap powder "Brillo".
An exhibition of his works in the Moderna Museet in 1968 exhibited - with Warhol's consent - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These were not (for cost reasons) from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo cartonage factory.
These were not works of art, but models, mere exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol probably granted permission in 1968 to produce a few Brillo wooden boxes in Sweden, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Contemporary witnesses now speak of around fifteen boxes that were rightly entered into art and auction history as authorized original Andy Warhol Brillo boxes labelled "Type Stockholm".
Some of them have earned more than $100,000 at auctions.
The problem is that legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that around a hundred wooden boxes had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, and that Warhol had left them to him.
In fact, Hultén’s 105 boxes were not produced until 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By that time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, Chief Conservator at the Moderna Museet, investigated three privately owned Swedish Brillo boxes, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their pressed chipboards were first primered and smeared, then white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the copies from 1990, on the other hand, reveals that the paint was applied directly to the pressed chipboard with a paint roller without primer - besides, it is not oil-, but acrylic paint.
“These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol’s Brillo boxes,” Moderna Museet director Lars Nittve said, “If the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York does not come to a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition material.”
Already in July, however, the Authentication Board announced to investigate the "serious allegations" that are being made in the matter of soap powder boxes.
Since then, however, they have remained in relentless silence.
Rebel soldiers in Manila give up
In the Philippines, rebels have abandoned soldiers, who had enclosed themselves in a hotel in Manila and demanded the overthrow of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
He cannot be responsible for bloodshed, the leader Antonio Trillanes, who accused the president of corruption and election fraud, told reporters at the hotel.
Government-loyal soldiers had previously stormed the hotel under tear gas use.
The two dozen soldiers had been hiding in the building for hours.
Approximately half of them went to court on Thursday for a failed coup attempt in 2003 – among them Trillanes.
He used the trial to suddenly settle with around 30 sympathizers.
The military police officers who were supposed to guard him had apparently turned over to him and joined his mutiny.
They invaded the Peninsula hotel and demanded the overthrow of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Loyal government troops closed off the district around the prestigious hotel.
The President convened an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
National Security Adviser Norberto Gonzales condemned the actions of the soldiers.
“People have enough,” Trillanes said.
"We call on people to join us."
General Danilo Lim, who formerly commanded the Scout Rangers elite unit, said other army units wanted to join the march shortly.
Government critics called for major demonstrations against the president on Friday.
Their government has been overshadowed by corruption allegations for months.
As early as 2003, Manila’s financial district was the main scene of the attempted mutiny of around 200 military members against Arroyo.
The uprising failed after nearly 24 hours due to the army’s refusal to join.
Since 1986, there have been at least seven coup attempts against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
